# Lint rules

All lints live in `tools/mockspace/lint-rules/`. `cargo mock` depends on this
crate. Every lint has tests. Every enforceable rule has a lint.

## Severity system

Every lint declares three independent gate levels: what happens on commit, on
build, and on push. No single-gate concept; all three gates are always active.

Four levels per gate: **error** (blocks), **warn** (prominent, no block),
**info** (reported, no block), **pass** (silent).

Named presets (convenience constants, all lints use the full three-gate struct):

| Preset | Commit | Build | Push | Use case |
|--------|--------|-------|------|----------|
| `HARD_ERROR` | error | error | error | Critical invariants |
| `BUILD_GATE` | warn | error | error | Must fix before building |
| `PUSH_GATE` | warn | warn | error | Clean before sharing |
| `ADVISORY` | warn | warn | warn | Never blocks |
| `INFO_ONLY` | info | info | info | Informational |

Three validation modes (from CLI flags):

| Flag | Mode | Who uses it |
|------|------|-------------|
| `--commit` | Commit | Pre-commit hook |
| _(default)_ | Build | Standalone `cargo mock`, CI |
| `--strict` | Push | Pre-push hook |

## Per-crate lints

| Lint | Preset | What it catches | Fix |
|------|--------|----------------|-----|
| `no-toml-value` | HARD_ERROR | `toml::Value` outside `polka-data` | Use `DataValue` trait from SDK |
| `no-ui-below-cli` | HARD_ERROR | `&Ui` parameter in non-CLI crates | Return structured results instead |
| `no-concrete-in-sdk` | HARD_ERROR | Concrete implementations in SDK crates | SDK exports only traits and `repr(C)` types |
| `no-upward-dep` | HARD_ERROR | Extension depending on non-SDK crate | Extensions depend on `polka-sdk` only |
| `no-direct-parse` | HARD_ERROR | Direct `polka.toml` parsing outside `polka-project` | Use `polka-project::load()` |
| `no-dyn` | HARD_ERROR | `dyn Trait` in framework code | Use trait-based dispatch or enum wrappers |
| `no-std-any` | HARD_ERROR | `std::any::TypeId` or type erasure | Use typed dispatch |
| `file-size` | HARD_ERROR | Files over 500 LOC | Split into multiple files |
| `export-count` | ADVISORY | More than 5 `pub` items at module root | Split into submodules |
| `no-todo` | PUSH_GATE | `todo!()` in source | Implement the function |

## Cross-crate lints

| Lint | Preset | What it catches | Fix |
|------|--------|----------------|-----|
| `no-duplicate-fn` | HARD_ERROR | Functions with matching signatures across crates | Extract to shared crate, reuse |
| `single-source` | HARD_ERROR | Same type name defined in multiple crates | One definition per concept |
| `undocumented-type` | BUILD_GATE | Source type not mentioned in any design doc | Add to DESIGN.md.tmpl or SHAME.md.tmpl (50+ words) |
| `changelist-doc-gate` | HARD_ERROR | Doc template edits when no doc changelist exists (TOPIC phase) | Write a doc changelist first to enter DOC phase |
| `changelist-lock` | HARD_ERROR | Doc template edits while doc changelist is locked (SRC-PLAN/SRC/DONE) | Doc edits only in DOC phase; use SHAME.md.tmpl for gaps |
| `changelist-required` | HARD_ERROR | Source edits without a source changelist (TOPIC/DOC/SRC-PLAN) | Create a source changelist to enter SRC phase |
| `changelist-immutability` | HARD_ERROR | Edits to a locked or deprecated changelist | Changelist is frozen; use SHAME.md.tmpl or deprecate to revise |

## SHAME paradigm

When `undocumented-type` blocks a type, you have two options:

1. **Proper fix**: add the type to DESIGN.md.tmpl via a design round.
2. **Temporary unblock**: create `SHAME.md.tmpl` in the crate directory with
   a `## TypeName` section containing 50+ words explaining why the type exists
   and how it will be properly documented. This downgrades the violation to
   ADVISORY (warn everywhere, never blocks).

SHAME entries are technical debt. They unblock iteration but must be resolved.

## Git hooks

| Hook | What it catches | Mode |
|------|----------------|------|
| `pre-commit` | cargo check + all lints | Commit (most permissive) |
| `commit-msg` | Commit message format, byline policy | Pre-commit |
| `pre-push` | cargo check + cargo test + all lints | Push (most strict) |

**Scoped commits:** the pre-commit hook extracts crate names from staged files
and passes `--scope crate1,crate2` to `cargo mock`. Only those crates are linted.
Infrastructure-only commits (lint rules, mockspace, hooks, agent templates) have no
crates in scope, so no lints run and the commit proceeds. This allows committing
lint improvements that detect existing violations without requiring all violations
to be fixed in the same commit. Cargo check always runs regardless of scope.

## No exceptions policy

If a lint flags something, the code MUST be fixed. Never add exceptions, never
add `#[allow]` attributes, never add crates to exempt lists without explicit
approval.

Exempt crates are hard-coded per lint (e.g., `polka-data` for `no-toml-value`,
`polka-derive` for proc macro internals). These exemptions exist because those
crates define the infrastructure the lint enforces.

Items marked with `// lint:allow(<rule>)` can be suppressed per-line.
Explained suppressions (8+ words after `--`) become ADVISORY; unexplained
ones stay at their original severity.

## Running lints

```bash
# Standalone build mode (default -- BUILD_GATE lints block)
cargo mock --lint-only

# Commit mode (most permissive -- only HARD_ERROR blocks)
cargo mock --lint-only --commit

# Push mode (most strict -- everything that can block, blocks)
cargo mock --lint-only --strict

# Full pipeline (check + lint + docs)
cargo mock

# Run lint tests
cd tools/mockspace/lint-rules && cargo test
```

## Adding a new lint

You MUST add a lint when adding any enforceable rule to PRINCIPLES, WORKFLOW,
or agent instructions. The rule does not exist until the lint exists.

1. Add a new file in `tools/mockspace/lint-rules/src/`
2. Implement the `Lint` trait (per-crate) or `CrossCrateLint` trait (cross-crate)
3. Declare severity using `Severity::new(on_commit, on_build, on_push)` or a preset
4. Register it in `tools/mockspace/lint-rules/src/lib.rs`
5. Write tests in `tools/mockspace/lint-rules/tests/lint_tests.rs`
6. Update this skill's lint table
7. Run `cargo test` in the lint-rules crate to verify
